Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship
left to right direction

actor "Floor Supervisor" as Supervisor
actor "Maintenance Technician" as Technician

rectangle "Factory Floor Management System" {
  usecase "Monitor Production Line" as UC1
  usecase "Schedule Production Run" as UC2
  usecase "Allocate Machine Resources" as UC3
  usecase "Report Equipment Fault" as UC4
  usecase "Log Maintenance Activity" as UC5
}

Supervisor -- UC1
Supervisor -- UC2
UC2 ..> UC3 : <<include>>
Technician -- UC4
Technician -- UC5
@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Schedule Production Run (UC2), Allocate Machine Resources (UC3), Include relationship from UC2 to UC3
   Explanation: "Allocate Machine Resources" (UC3) is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Schedule Production Run" / UC2). UC3 is not associated with any actor directly — no actor interacts with it. UC3 does not include, extend, generalize, or get extended by any other use case. It merely represents a sub-step of scheduling a production run (allocating the machines), not a complete service observable to any user. This is a textbook instance of Functional Decomposition via the include relationship: the base use case's internal behavior has been improperly decomposed into a separate inclusion use case that provides no standalone value.
